People, Ideas and Things that could help:\n\n[img[thesun]]\n\nWhen I look at this card, I am knocked away by the utter radiance and optimism it inspires. A man throws his head back and allows his personal energy to flow from his heart chakra. The world around him is vibrant and full of life. \n\nThis card encourages one to carry their "personal sun" with them whenever they need it most. This center of love, optimism, self-esteem, self-worth, and self-reliance can be used to overcome self-doubt and outside challenges.\n\nWhen I see this card, I am reminded that however many times I am rejected, or end up learning something the hard way, I am capable of getting up again and going forward. I rememeber that even if my actions fail, I am not a failure myself; in fact, having the courage to put myself out there in the first place is an excellent first step.\n\nIn my job search, I must remember that I am capable of many things, that my positive traits will shine through, and even when I am flooded with self-doubt, that I am capable of carrying on and learning from my mistakes.\n\nA tarot teacher of mine once said that when you get either The Sun or The World card in a tarot reading, "the intensity of the reading is magnified a hundred times". Clearly the message of this card is going to be important to my life.\n\n[[back|read]]
Hidden or underlying factors:\n\n[img[9cups]]\n\nThe man in this card is surrounded by glowing cups and baskets. He is perfectly content, and his energy is radiant. He is participating in giving openly and receiving freely. \n\nThe idea behind this card is that when one gives openly, of time, patience, energy, and appreciation, they will receive plenty in return. It refers to an exchange of energy.\n\nFor me, this card represents the concept of "you will get out of this what you put into it". In the past this idea has largely defined the experience of school for me; If I studied, did my homework, and went to a professor's office hours, I would do well. If I avoided my work and my professor, I would usually end up dropping the class.\n\nThe concept applies well to a job search, too. I am perfectly capable of getting a job, so long as I put in the time and energy to create a useful resume, research companies I would like to work for, present professionally, and contact employers frequently. If I am willing to dedicate that time and energy, it will pay off. If I am too scared to try, nothing will come of it. \n\nSo the card's message is simple: I need to remember that in order to get what I want, I need to give my time, energy, and patience to begin with. \n\n[[back|read]]
This reading looks at five factors.\n\n1. Subject/Nature of [[problem]]\n2. Particular [[Challenges]]\n3. Hidden and underlying [[factors]]\n4. People, ideas, or things that can [[help]]\n5. [[Actions]] needed to improve success

Actions I can take to improve my success:\n\n[img[thewanderer]]\n\nThis is one of my favorite cards of The Wildwood Tarot, and the one that convinced me to buy the deck in the first place. The Wanderer is a naive, humble, gender-ambiguous character going off on a journey into the unknown. They are excited, optimistic, and ready to have a fresh start.\n\nBeing gender queer, I easily see myself in this card, and it is usually the one I identify myself with. However, because I suffer from anxiety, I am often too fearful to embrace this happy-go-lucky, optimistic side of myself. It is difficult for me to leave the mistakes and burdens of the past behind me, and embark on a new journey in my life.\n\nWhen I look at this card, I realized I am being called to change my attitude and approach to finding a job. Instead of worrying constantly about money, my appearance, or tiny details of the job search, I need to dive enthusiastically into the process and stay optimistic. \n\nIf I embody the spirit of the wanderer, and approach this job search with enthusiasm while being careful not to be careless, I am likely to find the success I am looking for.\n\n[[back|read]]\n\n
My Challenges:\n\n[img[theguardian]]\n\n[img[file]]\n\nThe cave bear is made of bones. There is no skin, no muscle, no blood, and no life to the bear. Although he is large and imposing, there is nothing keeping someone from pushing against him lightly and knocking him over.\n\nThis card represents the self-built fears that prevent one from even considering entering the cave of their own darkness. When you tell yourself "I cannot look there", "this seems impossible", or "I don't trust myself", you're saving yourself from pain- but also from growth. \n\nThe challenges in my path are largely of my own creation. I want to self-sabotague my plans for getting a job because even the possibility of rejection is too painful to face. Far easier to never try than to admit to trying and failing.\n\nSo what to I need to overcome? Quite simply, I need to humble myself, push the bear aside, and plunge on in into my own cave of unknowing. I need to admit that I'm not perfect, that I don't know what I'm doing, and that it's totally okay to fuck up because I'm going to learn from the experience. I'm capable of becoming better through practice. \n\nAnd that's what I will do.\n\n[[back|read]]

Tarot Read; aka Go Get a Job
Toby Sparrow
My problem:\n\nThe Seven of Vessels. \n[img[7cups]]\n\nThis card indicates grief, and the idea of living through the memories of others.\n\nThe vessels present a choice: I can grieve for what I no longer have, or I can cry with gratitude for the options I have available to me. \n\nI mourn my former job, the security it offered, the opportunities for promotion, and the pleasure it gave me to have a somewhat meaningful retail position.\n\nCurrently I feel overwhelmed looking for a new job in a new town. I feel simultaneously like I cannot possibly meet every opportunity there is available, and also as though if I wait too long, there will be no opportunities left.\n\nThe card seems to be telling me that my issue is that I am living in the past, grieving over my former job to the point that I am blinded to the reality of current job opportunities. \n\nWhat I need to do is inventory what worked for me at my former job, what I learned from it, and what I would not repeat, and use that criteria to narrow down the options for a new job so I am not so overwhelmed. \n\nIt will also help to remember that I cannot completely live in the past, and that I need to define for myself what I need here and now.\n\n[[back|read]]
